comments: "Out in our meadow" is a traditional Swedish folk song first published in Gotland sometime during the 1880s, though it is also considered to have earlier origins as far back as the 1600s. The piece became widely published in the 1890s performed frequently by choral groups and has been described as a "national treasure" typically taught to schoolchildren. Also owing to this popularity is an arrangement of the piece by composer Hugo Alfvén in 1923.

name: I Wanna Be Around
comments: The story of “I Wanna Be Around” is legendary in the music business. Sadie Vimmerstedt, who lived in Youngstown, Ohio, was a big fan of Johnny Mercer’s music. She wrote the opening line ‘I want to be around to pick up the pieces, when somebody breaks yours heart’ and felt it sounded like a Johnny Mercer song. She mailed a letter to ‘Johnny Mercer, Songwriter, New York.’ The post office forwarded the letter to ASCAP (American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers), who got the letter to Mercer. Mercer wrote the melody himself and completed the lyrics for “I Wanna Be Around” in 1959 and asked Tony Bennett to record it, which he did in 1962. Mercer gave 50% of the profits to Ms. Vimmerstedt, which made her a wealthy woman and enabled her to retire and travel the world. It is one of the great songs in the American Songbook.

name: London Town
comments: Contains these lyrics from the song Green Rocky Road : "Green rocky road Promenade in green Tell me who y'all love" Michael "Mick" Taylor wrote this song and had been working with his producer, Peter Edens, to record it.  Edens had independently arranged to meet with a young Donovan to record some demos to pitch to the major labels. He presented the song to Donovan, he liked it and recorded a demo of it in Summer 1964 (but it never went any farther than a demo).  Taylor's version was completed and finally released in June 1965 to little acclaim (no videos exist or much of anything on Taylor - and you can't search for him as it only calls up the Rolling Stones guitarist, Mick Taylor ).  A friend of the producer's managed The Pretty Things and he heard the song and got them to release it on their Get the Picture? album.  In the book,  "The Autobiography of Donovan: The Hurdy Gurdy Man", pages 64-65, Donovan discusses the list of songs he was given to record and one was "London Town - written by Mick Taylor (after the Tim Hardin style)".  I also saw discussion from Edens that this song uses some lyrics from a folk song called " Green Rocky Road " that Hardin had recorded and when Donovan's recording finally was released decades later it credited Hardin, not Taylor.  I couldn't locate Hardin as an author of "London Town" in the PROs so it clearly must have been for his involvement with the "Green Rocky Road" song.

name: Six Strings Down
comments: Art Neville recorded a song in 1991 called "Another Blues Stringer", written by himself, Cyril Neville, Eric Kolb and Kelsey Smith.  Jimmie Vaughan released a song called "Six Strings Down" in 1994 that was a tribute to his brother, Stevie Ray Vaughan.  The registered authors are Jimmy Vaughan and the four above authors.  Although I couldn't locate specific mention of this on the Web, Vaughan's song is just a cover of Neville's song with additional lyrics added alluding to his brother and other guitar greats.
